Collections & Generics

In this Password Generator project, Collections and Generics are used to efficiently manage and store different types 
of characters used for generating passwords. They make the program flexible, type-safe, and easy to maintain.


1. Collections

Collections like ArrayList and List are used to store:
Uppercase letter
Lowercase letters
Digits

Special characters

Since collections are dynamic, the character list automatically adjusts based on user requirements.
This makes adding, removing, or modifying characters very easy.

Why Collections are useful

No fixed size like arrays

Fast iteration and random access

Easy to manage character sets

Ideal for generating random passwords



2. Generics

Generics ensure that the Collection contains only one specific type of element.

Example:
List<Character> ensures the list stores only characters.

Generics prevent errors and make the code cleaner and more reliable.

Why Generics are useful

Provides compile-time type safety

No need for type casting

Reduces bugs

Makes code easier to read and maintain




3. How Collections + Generics help the project

Characters are stored in type-safe lists

Password characters can be picked randomly and efficiently

The program becomes more flexible (easy to extend or customize)

Ensures only valid character data is processed



Java Code Using Collections & Generics

(Directly add this to your project)

import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Random;

public class PasswordGenerator {

    private int length;
    private List<Character> characterPool; // Using Collections & Generics

    public PasswordGenerator(int length) {
        this.length = length;
        this.characterPool = new ArrayList<>();
        loadDefaultCharacters();
    }

    private void loadDefaultCharacters() {
        String uppercase = "ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ";
        String lowercase = "abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz";
        String digits = "0123456789";
        String special = "@#$%&*!";

        addCharacters(uppercase);
        addCharacters(lowercase);
        addCharacters(digits);
        addCharacters(special);
    }

    private void addCharacters(String chars) {
        for (char c : chars.toCharArray()) {
            characterPool.add(c);
        }
    }

    public String generatePassword() {
        StringBuilder password = new StringBuilder();
        Random random = new Random();

        for (int i = 0; i < length; i++) {
            int index = random.nextInt(characterPool.size());
            password.append(characterPool.get(index));
        }

        return password.toString();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        PasswordGenerator pg = new PasswordGenerator(12);
        System.out.println("Generated Password: " + pg.generatePassword());
    }
}


